    {
      "content": "Basics of Authentication in Azure AD",
      "pos": [
        1674,
        1710
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are unfamiliar with basic concepts of authentication in Azure AD, read this section.",
      "pos": [
        1712,
        1803
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Otherwise, you may want to skip down to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Application Types and Scenarios<ept id=\"p1\">](#application-types-and-scenarios)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1804,
        1912
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Let’s consider the most basic scenario where identity is required: a user in a web browser needs to authenticate to a web application.",
      "pos": [
        1914,
        2048
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This scenario is described in greater detail in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Web Browser to Web Application<ept id=\"p1\">](#web-browser-to-web-application)</ept> section, but it’s a useful starting point to illustrate the capabilities of Azure AD and conceptualize how the scenario works.",
      "pos": [
        2049,
        2293
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider the following diagram for this scenario:",
      "pos": [
        2294,
        2343
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Overview of sign-on to web application",
      "pos": [
        2347,
        2385
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With the diagram above in mind, here’s what you need to know about its various components:",
      "pos": [
        2465,
        2555
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure AD is the identity provider, responsible for verifying the identity of users and applications that exist in an organization’s directory, and ultimately issuing security tokens upon successful authentication of those users and applications.",
      "pos": [
        2559,
        2804
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An application that wants to outsource authentication to Azure AD must be registered in Azure AD, which registers and uniquely identifies the app in the directory.",
      "pos": [
        2809,
        2972
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Developers can use the open source Azure AD authentication libraries to make authentication easy by handling the protocol details for you.",
      "pos": [
        2977,
        3115
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Active Directory Authentication Libraries<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-authentication-libraries.md)</ept> for more information.",
      "pos": [
        3116,
        3237
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "• Once a user has been authenticated, the application must validate the user’s security token to ensure that authentication was successful for the intended parties.",
      "pos": [
        3240,
        3404
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Developers can use the provided authentication libraries to handle validation of any token from Azure AD, including JSON Web Tokens (JWT) or SAML 2.0.",
      "pos": [
        3405,
        3555
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you want to perform validation manually, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>JWT Token Handler<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/dn205065(v=vs.110).aspx)</ept> documentation.",
      "pos": [
        3556,
        3702
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.IMPORTANT]</ph> Azure AD uses public key cryptography to sign tokens and verify that they are valid.",
      "pos": [
        3707,
        3809
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Important Information About Signing Key Rollover in Azure AD<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn641920.aspx)</ept> for more information on the necessary logic you must have in your application to ensure it’s always updated with the latest keys.",
      "pos": [
        3810,
        4062
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "• The flow of requests and responses for the authentication process is determined by the authentication protocol that was used, such as OAuth 2.0, OpenID Connect, WS-Federation, or SAML 2.0.",
      "pos": [
        4065,
        4255
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These protocols are discussed in more detail in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Active Directory Authentication Protocols<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn151124.aspx)</ept> topic and in the sections below.",
      "pos": [
        4256,
        4446
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Azure AD supports the OAuth 2.0 and OpenID Connect standards that make extensive use of bearer tokens, including bearer tokens represented as JWTs.",
      "pos": [
        4450,
        4610
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A bearer token is a lightweight security token that grants the “bearer” access to a protected resource.",
      "pos": [
        4611,
        4714
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this sense, the “bearer” is any party that can present the token.",
      "pos": [
        4715,
        4783
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Though a party must first authenticate with Azure AD to receive the bearer token, if the required steps are not taken to secure the token in transmission and storage, it can be intercepted and used by an unintended party.",
      "pos": [
        4784,
        5005
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While some security tokens have a built-in mechanism for preventing unauthorized parties from using them, bearer tokens do not have this mechanism and must be transported in a secure channel such as transport layer security (HTTPS).",
      "pos": [
        5006,
        5238
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If a bearer token is transmitted in the clear, a man-in the middle attack can be used by a malicious party to acquire the token and use it for an unauthorized access to a protected resource.",
      "pos": [
        5239,
        5429
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The same security principles apply when storing or caching bearer tokens for later use.",
      "pos": [
        5430,
        5517
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Always ensure that your application transmits and stores bearer tokens in a secure manner.",
      "pos": [
        5518,
        5608
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more security considerations on bearer tokens, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>RFC 6750 Section 5<ept id=\"p1\">](http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6750)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5609,
        5721
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Now that you have an overview of the basics, read the sections below to understand how provisioning works in Azure AD and the common scenarios Azure AD supports.",
      "pos": [
        5724,
        5885
      ]
    },
