    {
      "content": "Basics of Registering an Application in Azure AD",
      "pos": [
        8443,
        8491
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Any application that outsources authentication to Azure AD must be registered in a directory.",
      "pos": [
        8493,
        8586
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This step involves telling Azure AD about your application, including the URL where it’s located, the URL to send replies after authentication, the URI to identify your application, and more.",
      "pos": [
        8587,
        8778
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This information is required for a few key reasons:",
      "pos": [
        8779,
        8830
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure AD needs coordinates to communicate with the application when handling sign-on or exchanging tokens.",
      "pos": [
        8834,
        8940
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These include the following:",
      "pos": [
        8941,
        8969
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Application ID URI: The identifier for an application.",
      "pos": [
        8975,
        9029
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This value is sent to Azure AD during authentication to indicate which application the caller wants a token for.",
      "pos": [
        9030,
        9142
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Additionally, this value is included in the token so that the application knows it was the intended target.",
      "pos": [
        9143,
        9250
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Reply URL and Redirect URI: In the case of a web API or web application, the Reply URL is the location to which Azure AD will send the authentication response, including a token if authentication was successful.",
      "pos": [
        9257,
        9468
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the case of a native application, the Redirect URI is a unique identifier to which Azure AD will redirect the user-agent in an OAuth 2.0 request.",
      "pos": [
        9469,
        9617
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Client ID: The ID for an application, which is generated by Azure AD when the application is registered.",
      "pos": [
        9624,
        9728
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When requesting an authorization code or token, the client ID and key are sent to Azure AD during authentication.",
      "pos": [
        9729,
        9842
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Key: The key that is sent along with a client ID when authenticating to Azure AD to call a web API.",
      "pos": [
        9849,
        9948
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure AD needs to ensure the application has the required permissions to access your directory data, other applications in your organization, and so on",
      "pos": [
        9953,
        10104
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Provisioning becomes clearer when you understand that there are two categories of applications that can be developed and integrated with Azure AD:",
      "pos": [
        10106,
        10252
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single tenant application: A single tenant application is intended for use in one organization.",
      "pos": [
        10256,
        10351
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These are typically line-of-business (LoB) applications written by an enterprise developer.",
      "pos": [
        10352,
        10443
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A single tenant application only needs to be accessed by users in one directory, and as a result, it only needs to be provisioned in one directory.",
      "pos": [
        10444,
        10591
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These applications are typically registered by a developer in the organization.",
      "pos": [
        10592,
        10671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-tenant application: A multi-tenant application is intended for use in many organizations, not just one organization.",
      "pos": [
        10676,
        10798
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These are typically software-as-a-service (SaaS) applications written by an independent software vendor (ISV).",
      "pos": [
        10799,
        10909
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-tenant applications need to be provisioned in each directory where they will be used, which requires user or administrator consent to register them.",
      "pos": [
        10910,
        11064
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This consent process starts when an application has been registered in the directory and is given access to the Graph API or perhaps another web API.",
      "pos": [
        11065,
        11214
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When a user or administrator from a different organization signs up to use the application, they are presented with a dialog that displays the permissions the application requires.",
      "pos": [
        11215,
        11395
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The user or administrator can then consent to the application, which gives the application access to the stated data, and finally registers the application in their directory.",
      "pos": [
        11396,
        11571
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Overview of the Consent Framework<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-integrating-applications.md#overview-of-the-consent-framework)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        11572,
        11714
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Some additional considerations arise when developing a multi-tenant application instead of a single tenant application.",
      "pos": [
        11716,
        11835
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if you are making your application available to users in multiple directories, you need a mechanism to determine which tenant they’re in.",
      "pos": [
        11836,
        11986
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A single tenant application only needs to look in its own directory for a user, while a multi-tenant application needs to identify a specific user from all the directories in Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        11987,
        12171
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To accomplish this task, Azure AD provides a common authentication endpoint where any multi-tenant application can direct sign-in requests, instead of a tenant-specific endpoint.",
      "pos": [
        12172,
        12350
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This endpoint is https://login.microsoftonline.com/common for all directories in Azure AD, whereas a tenant-specific endpoint might be https://login.microsoftonline.com/contoso.onmicrosoft.com.",
      "pos": [
        12351,
        12544
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The common endpoint is especially important to consider when developing your application because you’ll need the necessary logic to handle multiple tenants during sign-in, sign-out, and token validation.",
      "pos": [
        12545,
        12748
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are currently developing a single tenant application but want to make it available to many organizations, you can easily make changes to the application and its configuration in Azure AD to make it multi-tenant capable.",
      "pos": [
        12750,
        12976
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, Azure AD uses the same signing key for all tokens in all directories, whether you are providing authentication in a single tenant or multi-tenant application.",
      "pos": [
        12977,
        13148
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each scenario listed in this document includes a sub-section that describes its provisioning requirements.",
      "pos": [
        13150,
        13256
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more in-depth information about provisioning an application in Azure AD and the differences between single and multi-tenant applications, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Integrating Applications with Azure Active Directory<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-integrating-applications.md)</ept> for more information.",
      "pos": [
        13257,
        13525
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Continue reading to understand the common application scenarios in Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        13526,
        13602
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Application Types and Scenarios",
      "pos": [
        13607,
        13638
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each of the scenarios described in this document can be developed using various languages and platforms, and there are <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>complete code samples available on GitHub<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/AzureADSamples)</ept> for each of them.",
      "pos": [
        13640,
        13855
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, if your application needs a specific piece or segment of an end-to-end scenario, in most cases that functionality can be added independently.",
      "pos": [
        13856,
        14010
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if you have a native application that calls a web API, you can easily add a web application that also calls the web API.",
      "pos": [
        14011,
        14144
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following diagram illustrates these scenarios and application types, and how different components can be added:",
      "pos": [
        14145,
        14260
      ]
    },
