      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Web Browser to Web Application<ept id=\"p1\">](#web-browser-to-web-application)</ept>: A user needs to sign in to a web application that is secured by Azure AD."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        14604,
        14748
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Single Page Application (SPA)<ept id=\"p1\">](#single-page-application-spa)</ept>: A user needs to sign in to a single page application that is secured by Azure AD."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        14752,
        14963
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Native Application to Web API<ept id=\"p1\">](#native-application-to-web-api)</ept>: A native application that runs on a phone, tablet, or PC needs to authenticate a user to get resources from a web API that is secured by Azure AD."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        14967,
        15102
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Web Application to Web API<ept id=\"p1\">](#web-application-to-web-api)</ept>: A web application needs to get resources from a web API secured by Azure AD."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        15106,
        15321
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Daemon or Server Application to Web API<ept id=\"p1\">](#daemon-or-server-application-to-web-api)</ept>: A daemon application or a server application with no web user interface needs to get resources from a web API secured by Azure AD."
    },
    {
      "content": "Web Browser to Web Application",
      "pos": [
        15327,
        15357
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This section describes an application that authenticates a user in a web browser to a web application.",
      "pos": [
        15359,
        15461
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this scenario, the web application directs the user’s browser to sign them in to Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        15462,
        15555
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure AD returns a sign-in response through the user’s browser, which contains claims about the user in a security token.",
      "pos": [
        15556,
        15677
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This scenario supports sign-on using the WS-Federation, SAML 2.0, and OpenID Connect protocols.",
      "pos": [
        15678,
        15773
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Diagram",
      "pos": [
        15781,
        15788
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Authentication flow for browser to web application",
      "pos": [
        15791,
        15841
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Description of Protocol Flow",
      "pos": [
        15928,
        15956
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When a user visits the application and needs to sign in, they are redirected via a sign-in request to the authentication endpoint in Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        15962,
        16104
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The user signs in on the sign-in page.",
      "pos": [
        16110,
        16148
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If authentication is successful, Azure AD creates an authentication token and returns a sign-in response to the application’s Reply URL that was configured in the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        16154,
        16341
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For a production application, this Reply URL should be HTTPS.",
      "pos": [
        16342,
        16403
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The returned token includes claims about the user and Azure AD that are required by the application to validate the token.",
      "pos": [
        16404,
        16526
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application validates the token by using a public signing key and issuer information available at the federation metadata document for Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        16532,
        16680
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the application validates the token, Azure AD starts a new session with the user.",
      "pos": [
        16681,
        16768
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This session allows the user to access the application until it expires.",
      "pos": [
        16769,
        16841
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Code Samples",
      "pos": [
        16849,
        16861
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See the code samples for Web Browser to Web Application scenarios.",
      "pos": [
        16864,
        16930
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "And, check back frequently -- we add new samples all the time.",
      "pos": [
        16931,
        16993
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Web Browser to Web Application<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-code-samples.md#web-browser-to-web-application)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        16994,
        17092
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Registering",
      "pos": [
        17100,
        17111
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single Tenant: If you are building an application just for your organization, it must be registered in your company’s directory by using the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        17116,
        17281
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-Tenant: If you are building an application that can be used by users outside your organization, it must be registered in your company’s directory, but also must be registered in each organization’s directory that will be using the application.",
      "pos": [
        17286,
        17535
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To make your application available in their directory, you can include a sign-up process for your customers that enables them to consent to your application.",
      "pos": [
        17536,
        17693
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When they sign up for your application, they will be presented with a dialog that shows the permissions the application requires, and then the option to consent.",
      "pos": [
        17694,
        17855
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Depending on the required permissions, an administrator in the other organization may be required to give consent.",
      "pos": [
        17856,
        17970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the user or administrator consents, the application is registered in their directory.",
      "pos": [
        17971,
        18061
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Integrating Applications with Azure Active Directory<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-integrating-applications.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        18062,
        18189
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Token Expiration",
      "pos": [
        18197,
        18213
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The user’s session expires when the lifetime of the token issued by Azure AD expires.",
      "pos": [
        18215,
        18300
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Your application can shorten this time period if desired, such as signing out users based on a period of inactivity.",
      "pos": [
        18301,
        18417
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the session expires, the user will be prompted to sign in again.",
      "pos": [
        18418,
        18487
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single Page Application (SPA)",
      "pos": [
        18497,
        18526
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This section describes authentication for a single page application that uses Azure AD to secure its web API back end.",
      "pos": [
        18529,
        18647
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single page applications are typically structured as a JavaScript presentation layer (front end) that runs in the browser and a web API back end that runs on a server and implements the application’s business logic.",
      "pos": [
        18648,
        18863
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this scenario, when the user signs in, the JavaScript front end uses <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Active Directory Authentication Library for JavaScript (ADAL.JS)<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/AzureAD/azure-activedirectory-library-for-js/tree/dev)</ept> preview and the OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant protocol to obtain an ID token (id_token) from Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        18864,
        19174
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The token is cached and the client attaches it to the request as the bearer token when making calls to its web API back end, which is secured using the OWIN middleware.",
      "pos": [
        19175,
        19343
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Diagram",
      "pos": [
        19351,
        19358
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single Page Application diagram",
      "pos": [
        19362,
        19393
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Description of Protocol Flow",
      "pos": [
        19472,
        19500
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The user navigates to the web application.",
      "pos": [
        19505,
        19547
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application returns the JavaScript front end (presentation layer) to the browser.",
      "pos": [
        19553,
        19638
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The user initiates sign in, for example by clicking a sign in link.",
      "pos": [
        19644,
        19711
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The browser sends a GET to the Azure AD authorization endpoint to request an ID token.",
      "pos": [
        19712,
        19798
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This request includes the client ID and reply URL in the query parameters.",
      "pos": [
        19799,
        19873
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure AD validates the Reply URL against the registered Reply URL that was configured in the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        19879,
        19996
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The user signs in on the sign-in page.",
      "pos": [
        20002,
        20040
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If authentication is successful, Azure AD creates an ID token and returns it as a URL fragment (#) to the application’s Reply URL.",
      "pos": [
        20046,
        20176
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For a production application, this Reply URL should be HTTPS.",
      "pos": [
        20177,
        20238
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The returned token includes claims about the user and Azure AD that are required by the application to validate the token.",
      "pos": [
        20239,
        20361
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The JavaScript client code running in the browser extracts the token from the response to use in securing calls to the application’s web API back end.",
      "pos": [
        20367,
        20517
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The browser calls the application’s web API back end with the access token in the authorization header.",
      "pos": [
        20523,
        20626
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Code Samples",
      "pos": [
        20633,
        20645
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See the code samples for Single Page Application (SPA) scenarios.",
      "pos": [
        20648,
        20713
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Be sure to check back frequently -- we add new samples all the time.",
      "pos": [
        20714,
        20782
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Single Page Application (SPA)<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-code-samples.md#single-page-application-spa)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        20783,
        20877
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Registering",
      "pos": [
        20885,
        20896
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single Tenant: If you are building an application just for your organization, it must be registered in your company’s directory by using the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        20901,
        21066
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-Tenant: If you are building an application that can be used by users outside your organization, it must be registered in your company’s directory, but also must be registered in each organization’s directory that will be using the application.",
      "pos": [
        21071,
        21320
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To make your application available in their directory, you can include a sign-up process for your customers that enables them to consent to your application.",
      "pos": [
        21321,
        21478
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When they sign up for your application, they will be presented with a dialog that shows the permissions the application requires, and then the option to consent.",
      "pos": [
        21479,
        21640
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Depending on the required permissions, an administrator in the other organization may be required to give consent.",
      "pos": [
        21641,
        21755
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the user or administrator consents, the application is registered in their directory.",
      "pos": [
        21756,
        21846
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Integrating Applications with Azure Active Directory<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-integrating-applications.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        21847,
        21974
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After registering the application, it must be configured to use OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant protocol.",
      "pos": [
        21976,
        22074
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, this protocol is disabled for applications.",
      "pos": [
        22075,
        22130
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To enable the OAuth2 Implicit Grant protocol for your application, download its application manifest from the Azure Management Portal, set the “oauth2AllowImplicitFlow” value to true, and then upload the manifest back to the portal.",
      "pos": [
        22131,
        22363
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For detailed instructions, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enabling OAuth 2.0 Implicit Grant for Single Page Applications<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-integrating-applications.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        22364,
        22506
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Token Expiration",
      "pos": [
        22514,
        22530
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you use ADAL.js to manage authentication with Azure AD, you benefit from several features that facilitate refreshing an expired token as well as getting tokens for additional web API resources that may be called by the application.",
      "pos": [
        22532,
        22768
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the user successfully authenticates with Azure AD, a session secured by a cookie is established for the user between the browser and Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        22769,
        22916
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It’s important to note that the session exists between the user and Azure AD and not between the user and the web application running on the server.",
      "pos": [
        22917,
        23065
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When a token expires, ADAL.js uses this session to silently obtain another token.",
      "pos": [
        23066,
        23147
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It does this by using a hidden iFrame to send and receive the request using the OAuth Implicit Grant protocol.",
      "pos": [
        23148,
        23258
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "ADAL.js can also use this same mechanism to silently obtain access tokens from Azure AD for other web API resources that the application calls as long as these resources support cross-origin resource sharing (CORS), are registered in the user’s directory, and any required consent was given by the user during sign-in.",
      "pos": [
        23259,
        23577
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Native Application to Web API",
      "pos": [
        23584,
        23613
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This section describes a native application that calls a web API on behalf of a user.",
      "pos": [
        23616,
        23701
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This scenario is built on the OAuth 2.0 authorization code grant type with a public client, as described in section 4.1 of the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>OAuth 2.0 specification<ept id=\"p1\">](http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6749)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        23702,
        23891
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The native application obtains an access token for the user by using the OAuth 2.0 protocol.",
      "pos": [
        23892,
        23984
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This access token is then sent in the request to the web API, which authorizes the user and returns the desired resource.",
      "pos": [
        23985,
        24106
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Diagram",
      "pos": [
        24113,
        24120
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Native Application to Web API Diagram",
      "pos": [
        24124,
        24161
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Authentication flow for native application to API",
      "pos": [
        24246,
        24295
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Description of Protocol Flow",
      "pos": [
        24302,
        24330
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are using the AD Authentication Libraries, most of the protocol details described below are handled for you, such as the browser pop-up, token caching, and handling of refresh tokens.",
      "pos": [
        24333,
        24523
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using a browser pop-up, the native application makes a request to the authorization endpoint in Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        24528,
        24633
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This request includes the client ID and the redirect URI of the native application as shown in the Management Portal, and the application ID URI for the web API.",
      "pos": [
        24634,
        24795
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the user hasn’t already signed in, they are prompted to sign in again",
      "pos": [
        24796,
        24868
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure AD authenticates the user.",
      "pos": [
        24874,
        24906
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If it is a multi-tenant application and consent is required to use the application, the user will be required to consent if they haven’t already done so.",
      "pos": [
        24907,
        25060
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After granting consent and upon successful authentication, Azure AD issues an authorization code response back to the client application’s redirect URI.",
      "pos": [
        25061,
        25213
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When Azure AD issues an authorization code response back to the redirect URI, the client application stops browser interaction and extracts the authorization code from the response.",
      "pos": [
        25219,
        25400
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using this authorization code, the client application sends a request to Azure AD’s token endpoint that includes the authorization code, details about the client application (client ID and redirect URI), and the desired resource (application ID URI for the web API).",
      "pos": [
        25401,
        25667
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The authorization code and information about the client application and web API are validated by Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        25673,
        25779
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Upon successful validation, Azure AD returns two tokens: a JWT access token and a JWT refresh token.",
      "pos": [
        25780,
        25880
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, Azure AD returns basic information about the user, such as their display name and tenant ID.",
      "pos": [
        25881,
        25986
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Over HTTPS, the client application uses the returned JWT access token to add the JWT string with a “Bearer” designation in the Authorization header of the request to the web API.",
      "pos": [
        25992,
        26170
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The web API then validates the JWT token, and if validation is successful, returns the desired resource.",
      "pos": [
        26171,
        26275
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the access token expires, the client application will receive an error that indicates the user needs to authenticate again.",
      "pos": [
        26281,
        26409
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the application has a valid refresh token, it can be used to acquire a new access token without prompting the user to sign in again.",
      "pos": [
        26410,
        26545
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the refresh token expires, the application will need to interactively authenticate the user once again.",
      "pos": [
        26546,
        26652
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The refresh token issued by Azure AD can be used to access multiple resources.",
      "pos": [
        26657,
        26748
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if you have a client application that has permission to call two web APIs, the refresh token can be used to get an access token to the other web API as well.",
      "pos": [
        26749,
        26919
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Code Samples",
      "pos": [
        26927,
        26939
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See the code samples for Native Application to Web API scenarios.",
      "pos": [
        26942,
        27007
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "And, check back frequently -- we add new samples all the time.",
      "pos": [
        27008,
        27070
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Native Application to Web API<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-code-samples.md#native-application-to-web-api)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        27071,
        27167
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Registering",
      "pos": [
        27175,
        27186
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single Tenant: Both the native application and the web API must be registered in the same directory in Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        27191,
        27303
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The web API can be configured to expose a set of permissions, which are used to limit the native application’s access to its resources.",
      "pos": [
        27304,
        27439
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The client application then selects the desired permissions from the “Permissions to Other Applications” drop-down menu in the Azure Management Portal.",
      "pos": [
        27440,
        27591
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-Tenant: First, the native application only ever registered in the developer or publisher’s directory.",
      "pos": [
        27596,
        27703
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Second, the native application is configured to indicate the permissions it requires to be functional.",
      "pos": [
        27704,
        27806
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This list of required permissions is shown in a dialog when a user or administrator in the destination directory gives consent to the application, which makes it available to their organization.",
      "pos": [
        27807,
        28001
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Some applications require just user-level permissions, which any user in the organization can consent to.",
      "pos": [
        28002,
        28107
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Other applications require administrator-level permissions, which a user in the organization cannot consent to.",
      "pos": [
        28108,
        28219
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Only a directory administrator can give consent to applications that require this level of permissions.",
      "pos": [
        28220,
        28323
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the user or administrator consents, only the web API is registered in their directory.",
      "pos": [
        28324,
        28415
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Integrating Applications with Azure Active Directory<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-integrating-applications.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        28416,
        28543
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Token Expiration",
      "pos": [
        28551,
        28567
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the native application uses its authorization code to get a JWT access token, it also receives a JWT refresh token.",
      "pos": [
        28570,
        28690
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the access token expires, the refresh token can be used to re-authenticate the user without requiring them to sign in again.",
      "pos": [
        28691,
        28820
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This refresh token is then used to authenticate the user, which results in a new access token and refresh token.",
      "pos": [
        28821,
        28933
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Web Application to Web API",
      "pos": [
        28943,
        28969
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This section describes a web application that needs to get resources from a web API.",
      "pos": [
        28972,
        29056
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this scenario, there are two identity types that the web application can use to authenticate and call the web API: an application identity, or a delegated user identity.",
      "pos": [
        29057,
        29229
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For the application identity type, this scenario uses OAuth 2.0 client credentials grant to authenticate as the application and access the web API.",
      "pos": [
        29230,
        29377
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When using an application identity, the web API can only detect that the web application is calling it, as the web API does not receive any information about the user.",
      "pos": [
        29378,
        29545
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the application receives information about the user, it will be sent via the application protocol, and it is not signed by Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        29546,
        29681
      ]
    },
    {
